The grammar has the rule S → NT6 NT30.  
NT6 → 't23' and NT30 → 't16',  
so S ⇒ NT6 NT30 ⇒ t23 t16.  
Yes

We need a derivation S ⇒ X Y with X ⇒ t3 and Y ⇒ t38 (since the target string has length 2). The two CNF rules for S are

 1. S → NT13 NT22  
 2. S → NT6 NT30

Case 1: S → NT13 NT22  
· NT13 ⇒ {t1, t2} only, so it cannot yield t3.  
Case 2: S → NT6 NT30  
· NT6 ⇒ {t23, t6, t8, t18, t12} only, so it cannot yield t3.  
Moreover, in order to get t38 from NT30 you’d have to expand NT30 → NT23 NT32, which would give a 3‐token string, not 2. No other expansion produces t38 in the second position within a 2‐terminal yield.  

Therefore the grammar cannot generate “t3 t38.”  
No

To derive a length‑2 string, the only productions from S are

  S → NT6 NT30  
  S → NT13 NT22  

We need the first nonterminal to yield “t30” and the second to yield “t33.”  

1. If S → NT6 NT30, then NT30 → 't33' is possible, but NT6 only ever yields one of {t23, t6, t8, t18, t12}, never t30.  
2. If S → NT13 NT22, then NT22 can yield 't30', but NT13 only yields {t1, t2}, never t33 (and the order is reversed anyway).  

No other routes produce exactly two terminals. Hence the grammar cannot generate “t30 t33.”  

No

To generate a 3‐token string in CNF, S must use the rule

  S → NT6 NT30

since S→NT13 NT22 only yields 2 tokens.  Then NT6 must cover the first token and NT30 the last two.  

1) The input’s first token is “t38”, but NT6 can only produce t23, t6, t8, t18 or t12.  So NT6 can’t match “t38”.  
2) Hence S→NT6 NT30 cannot cover “t38 t29 t2”.  

There is no other way to split/generate three tokens.  Therefore the grammar does *not* generate the string.

No

To generate a length‐3 string, the only possibility is

  S → NT6 NT30
      NT6 ⇒ t23  
      NT30 ⇒ NT23 NT32 ⇒ t29 t20

so S ⇒ t23 t29 t20.  That is the only length‐3 yield, and it begins with t23, not t3.  Hence the grammar cannot produce t3 t23 t20.  
No

To check if S ⇒* t6 t34 t35 t38, we run the CYK algorithm:

1) Terminals:
   pos1 t6  ⇒ NT6  
   pos2 t34 ⇒ NT21, NT32, NT11  
   pos3 t35 ⇒ NT22, NT11  
   pos4 t38 ⇒ NT32  

2) Length‐2 spans:
   (2–3): (NT21,NT11) ⇒ NT23  
   (2–4): from (2–3)=NT23 and (4)=NT32 ⇒ NT30  

3) Length‐4 span (1–4):
   (1)=NT6 and (2–4)=NT30 ⇒ S  

Hence S generates the string.  
Yes

To decide if S ⇒* t8 t34 t35 t41, we run the CYK algorithm:

Terminals (length‑1 substrings):
1. t8  → NT6  
2. t34 → NT21, NT32, NT11  
3. t35 → NT22, NT11  
4. t41 → NT32  

Length‑2 substrings:
1–2 (t8 t34): {NT6}×{NT21,NT32,NT11} yields no rule  
2–3 (t34 t35): NT21 NT11 ⇒ NT23  
3–4 (t35 t41): {NT22,NT11}×{NT32} yields no rule  

Length‑3 substrings:
1–3 splits at 1 or 2: no combinations produce any NT  
2–4 splits at 2: NT23 NT32 ⇒ NT30  

Length‑4 substring (1–4):
Split at 1: NT6 NT30 ⇒ S

So S derives the entire string.  

Yes

We run the CYK algorithm on the input “t12 t34 t35 t34”:

1.  Length‐1 spans  
    position 1 (“t12”): NT6, NT11  
    position 2 (“t34”): NT21, NT11, NT32  
    position 3 (“t35”): NT11, NT22  
    position 4 (“t34”): NT21, NT11, NT32

2.  Length‐2 spans  
    (1–2): no binary rule matches → ∅  
    (2–3): NT21·NT11 ⇒ NT23  
    (3–4): no binary rule matches → ∅

3.  Length‐3 spans  
    (1–3): using (1–1)×(2–3) = {NT6,NT11}×{NT23} → no match; (1–2)×(3–3)=∅ → ∅  
    (2–4): using (2–3)×(4–4) = {NT23}×{NT21,NT11,NT32} we get NT30 by NT30→NT23 NT32

4.  Length‐4 span (1–4): test splits  
    (1–1)×(2–4) = {NT6,NT11}×{NT30} gives S→NT6 NT30  

Thus S covers (1–4), so the grammar generates the string.  
Yes

The start symbol S can only yield either  
 - 2 terminals via S → NT13 NT22 (each of those has only a terminal production), or  
 - 3 terminals via S → NT6 NT30 when NT30 → NT23 NT32 (NT6 gives 1 terminal, NT23 and NT32 each give 1 terminal).  

There is no way to derive 4 terminals. Hence the string of length 4 is not in the language.  

No

We can see that S has only two productions, each yielding either
• S→NT13 NT22 which produces exactly 2 terminals, or  
• S→NT6 NT30 which produces 1 (from NT6) + either 1 (if NT30→'t16','t33',… ) or 3 (if NT30→NT23 NT32→NT21 NT11 NT32) = 2 or 4 terminals.

To get a 4‐token string we must use S→NT6 NT30 with NT30→NT23 NT32 (so NT23→NT21 NT11 yields 2 tokens, NT32 yields 1 token). Then the first token of the string comes from NT6. But NT6 can only produce {t23, t6, t8, t18, t12} – never t16. Hence no derivation can start with t16. Therefore the string “t16 t20 t41 t30” is not generated.  

No

After examining the productions, the only way to start is  
S → NT6 NT30  
NT6 always yields exactly one terminal (one of t23, t6, t8, t18, t12)  
NT30 can yield at most three terminals (via NT23 NT32 → (NT21 NT11) NT32 → 2 + 1 leaves)  

So S can generate at most 1 + 3 = 4 terminals. Our target string has 5 terminals, and moreover its first token t16 cannot come from NT6. Hence the grammar cannot generate  “t16 t18 t12 t35 t23.”  

No

The grammar can only generate strings of length 2, 3, or 4 (by inspection of how S expands), but the given string has length 5. Hence it cannot be generated. 

No

We can observe that any derivation from S has the following forms and lengths:

1. S → NT13 NT22  
   NT13 and NT22 each produce exactly one terminal → total length = 2

2. S → NT6 NT30  
   • NT6 → one terminal (length 1)  
   • NT30 →  
     – one terminal (‘t16’, ‘t33’, or ‘t32’) ⇒ length 1 ⇒ S ⇒ total length 2  
     – NT23 NT32  
       · NT23 → either one terminal (‘t29’) or two terminals (via NT21 NT11) ⇒ length 1 or 2  
       · NT32 → exactly one terminal ⇒ length 1  
       ⇒ NT30 length = 1+1=2 or 2+1=3  
       ⇒ S total length = 1+2=3 or 1+3=4  

Hence all strings in L(G) have length 2, 3, or 4. The given string has length 5, so it cannot be generated.  

No

To generate a 6‑token string, S would have to expand to two nonterminals whose subtrees together yield six leaves.  But in this grammar

- S → NT13 NT22 always yields exactly 2 terminals (one from NT13, one from NT22).
- S → NT6 NT30 yields at most 4 terminals (1 from NT6 and at most 3 from NT30 via NT30→NT23 NT32→NT21 NT11 + NT32).

There is no way to get six tokens. Hence the string t29 t2 t6 t1 t23 t27 cannot be generated.  

No

To see why the 6‐token string cannot be generated, note that S only ever splits into two nonterminals:

 1. S → NT13 NT22  
 2. S → NT6 NT30  

Each of NT13, NT22, NT6, NT30 either goes straight to a single terminal or, in the case of NT30, can do one binary step:

  • NT30 → NT23 NT32  
  • NT23 → NT21 NT11  

Thus any S→NT13 NT22 yields exactly 2 terminals.  
And any S→NT6 NT30 yields either  
  – NT6→t (1 token) and NT30→t (1 token) = 2 tokens,  
  – or NT6→t (1 token), NT30→NT23 NT32 ⇒ NT23→NT21 NT11 (2 tokens) plus NT32→t (1 token) = 4 tokens.

No derivation ever spans 6 terminals. Since our string has length 6, it cannot be in L(G).  
No

To generate a length‑6 string, S would have to derive more than two symbols, but:

- S → NT13 NT22 always yields exactly 2 terminals (each of NT13 and NT22 only produce one terminal).
- S → NT6 NT30 yields length(1 + length(NT30)). NT6 produces 1 terminal, and NT30 can produce at most 3 terminals (NT30→NT23 NT32 with NT23→NT21 NT11 gives 2+1=3). So S can only produce lengths 2, 3, or 4.

Since 6 is out of reach, the given string cannot be generated.  
No

We can only derive strings of length at most 4 from S (S→NT6 NT30 yields at most 4 terminals, S→NT13 NT22 yields 2). Since the target string has length 7, it cannot be generated.  
No

After applying the CYK algorithm (or by observing that every derivation from S yields either 2 or 4 terminals, never 7), we see no way to generate a 7‐token string. 

No

We can observe that S has only two binary productions:

  S → NT13 NT22  
  S → NT6 NT30  

All other rules either produce a single terminal or (in NT30 and NT23) exactly two or three terminals, but there is no way to derive a total of 7 terminals under these constraints.  In fact:

– S→NT13 NT22 can only yield 1+1=2 terminals.  
– S→NT6 NT30, with NT30→terminal or NT30→NT23 NT32 (and NT23→terminal or NT23→NT21 NT11), can only yield 1+1=2 or 1+3=4 terminals.  

No derivation reaches length 7. Hence the given string is not in the language.  

No

We can observe that every derivation from S produces at most 4 terminals:

- S → NT13 NT22 ⇒ exactly 2 terminals.
- S → NT6 NT30 ⇒ NT6 gives 1 terminal; NT30 either directly 1 terminal, or NT23 NT32 giving at most 2+1=3 terminals. So S → NT6 NT30 yields at most 1+3=4 terminals.

Our target string has 7 tokens, so it cannot be generated.  
No

First, note that the only binary productions are

  S  → NT13 NT22  
  S  → NT6 NT30  
  NT23 → NT21 NT11  
  NT30 → NT23 NT32  

All other productions go straight to a single terminal.  Hence every nonterminal either emits exactly one terminal or, at most, in a single step emits two nonterminals, each of which in turn can only emit terminals (and NT23 even has a direct terminal‐rule as well as its binary rule).

Concretely:

– S→NT13 NT22 produces exactly 2 terminals.  
– S→NT6 NT30 gives  
   • if NT30→terminal, then NT6 and NT30 each emit 1 terminal ⇒ total length = 2  
   • if NT30→NT23 NT32 and NT23→terminal, NT32→terminal ⇒ NT30 emits 2 terminals ⇒ S emits 3 total  
   • if NT30→NT23 NT32 and NT23→NT21 NT11 (each terminal), NT32→terminal ⇒ NT30 emits 3 terminals ⇒ S emits 4 total  

There is no recursion, so the grammar can only generate strings of length 2, 3 or 4. The given string has length 8, so it cannot be generated.  

No

We can observe that S only ever expands to two nonterminals (S→NT13 NT22 or NT6 NT30).  Both NT13 and NT22 are terminals in one step (yielding 2‐letter strings), and NT6 is a terminal while NT30 either goes to a terminal (yielding 2 letters total) or to NT23 NT32.  NT23 in turn can either go directly to a terminal or split into NT21 NT11 (two terminals), and NT32 is always a single terminal.  Hence the maximum length S→NT6 NT30… can produce is 4 terminals, and S→NT13 NT22 produces exactly 2.  The given string has 9 tokens, so it cannot be generated.  
No

To see why the 9‐token string can’t be generated, note that the only binary productions are

  S  → NT13 NT22  
  S  → NT6  NT30  
  NT23 → NT21 NT11  
  NT30 → NT23 NT32  

and every other rule is of the form X → 't…' (a single terminal).  Thus any derivation from S must, at its top level, either

  1) use S → NT13 NT22, producing exactly 2 terminals (one from NT13, one from NT22), or  
  2) use S → NT6 NT30, where NT6 ⇒ one terminal and NT30 either ⇒ one terminal or ⇒ NT23 NT32 ⇒ 2 + 1 = 3 terminals, so in total 1+1=2 or 1+3=4 terminals.

No derivation from S can yield 9 terminals.  Therefore the given string of length 9 is not in the language.  

No

After examining the only way to generate an 11‑token string (S → NT6 NT30), NT6 must produce the first token t41—but NT6 can only produce t23, t6, t8, t18 or t12. No rule lets NT6 → t41, so the full string cannot be derived.  

No

After running the CYK‐style check, you can see that the start symbol S can only generate strings of length 2 or 4 in this grammar (it either expands to two terminals directly, or to four via one binary “chain” NT30→NT23 NT32→NT21 NT11 NT32). Since the target string has length 11, it cannot be generated.  

No

We run the CYK algorithm.  The only binary productions are
  S → NT13 NT22  
  S → NT6 NT30  
  NT23 → NT21 NT11  
  NT30 → NT23 NT32  
and all other productions go straight to a single terminal.  In the table of length‐1 spans we get nonterminals that produce each t‐symbol, but when we try to build any length‐2 span there is no adjacent pair of nonterminals matching the left‐ and right‐hand sides of one of those four binary rules.  Hence no span of length ≥2 ever acquires a nonterminal, so we can never build up to S over the full 12‐token input.  Therefore the grammar does not generate the string.  

No

After filling in the CYK table, no length‐>1 cell ever gets any nonterminals from the binary rules. In particular P(1,12) does not contain S, so the grammar cannot generate the string.

No

We observe that S has only two productions:

 1. S → NT13 NT22  
 2. S → NT6 NT30

Each of NT13, NT22, and NT6 produces exactly one terminal. NT30 either produces one terminal (t16, t33, or t32) or expands as NT23 NT32. In the latter case NT23→NT21 NT11 and NT21, NT11, NT32 each produce one terminal. Hence

– S→NT13 NT22 yields exactly 2 terminals.  
– S→NT6 (terminal) NT30→(terminal) yields 2 terminals.  
– S→NT6 (terminal) NT30→NT23 NT32→NT21 NT11 NT32 yields 4 terminals.

There is no recursion to generate longer strings. So the maximum length of any generated string is 4, far less than the 12 tokens of the given string. Therefore the grammar cannot generate it.

No

After filling the CYK table you find that the only way to derive an S over any length >1 is via S → NT6 NT30 on the adjacent pair t8 t33 (positions 6–7). No other S‐derivation ever appears (and you can’t build out to cover all 12 tokens). Hence the grammar does not generate the full string.

No

The grammar’s only binary expansions are
        
  S → NT6 NT30  
  S → NT13 NT22  
  NT30 → NT23 NT32  
  NT23 → NT21 NT11  

All other productions replace a nonterminal by a single terminal. Thus any derivation can introduce at most two binary splits: NT30→NT23 NT32 and NT23→NT21 NT11. Counting terminals:

  • If S→NT13 NT22, you get 2 terminals.  
  • If S→NT6 NT30 and NT30 uses only A→terminal, you get 2 terminals.  
  • If S→NT6 NT30 and NT30→NT23 NT32, NT23→NT21 NT11, you get 4 terminals (NT6,NT21,NT11,NT32).  

No derivation can yield more than 4 terminals, but the given string has 13 tokens. Therefore the grammar cannot generate it.  

No

We can observe that the only binary rules that expand S are  

  S → NT13 NT22  
  S → NT6 NT30  

and that neither NT13 nor NT22 has any further binary expansions (they only go to a single terminal).  Thus S → NT13 NT22 can only yield exactly 2 terminals.  

The other choice, S → NT6 NT30, can yield  
 –  NT6 (1 terminal) + NT30 (1 terminal) = 2 terminals, or  
 –  NT6 (1 terminal) + NT30 via NT23 NT32 = 1 + (2 + 1) = 4 terminals.  

No other binary recursion exists to grow the yield beyond length 4. But our target string has length 13, so it cannot be generated.  

No

We can observe that the only binary productions are

  S → NT13 NT22  
  S → NT6  NT30  
  NT23 → NT21 NT11  
  NT30 → NT23 NT32  

all other productions map a nonterminal directly to a single terminal.  In CNF any nonterminal that only has terminal‐producing rules can yield exactly one terminal, and any binary production increases the yield length by exactly the sum of its two children.  Tracking possible yields:

- From S→NT13 NT22, both NT13 and NT22 must each produce exactly one terminal ⇒ total length 2.  
- From S→NT6 NT30, NT6 produces 1 terminal, NT30 either  
    • directly produces 1 terminal (via a unary rule), giving length 2 overall, or  
    • uses NT30→NT23 NT32, where NT32 produces 1 terminal and NT23→NT21 NT11 yields exactly 2 terminals ⇒ NT30 yields 3 terminals, so S yields 1+3=4 terminals.

No other binary expansions exist, so S can only generate strings of length 2 or 4. The given string has length 15, so it cannot be generated.  

No

After inspecting the productions, S can only derive strings of length 2 or 4 (there’s no recursion to build longer strings). The given string has length 16, so it cannot be generated.

To derive a string from S in this CNF grammar, its first terminal must come from either NT13 (if we use S→NT13 NT22) or NT6 (if we use S→NT6 NT30).  
• NT13 can only produce ‘t1’ or ‘t2’.  
• NT6 can only produce one of {‘t23’, ‘t6’, ‘t8’, ‘t18’, ‘t12’}.  

But the given string begins with ‘t27’, which neither NT13 nor NT6 can generate. Hence it is impossible to derive the string from S.

We observe that every derivation from S in this CNF grammar produces at most three terminals:

1. S → NT13 NT22  
   Both NT13 and NT22 only ever go to a single terminal each ⇒ yields exactly 2 terminals.

2. S → NT6 NT30  
   a) If NT30 → a terminal, then NT6 and NT30 each yield one terminal ⇒ 2 terminals total.  
   b) If NT30 → NT23 NT32, then S ⇒ NT6 NT23 NT32, and each of NT6, NT23, NT32 only ever goes to exactly one terminal ⇒ 3 terminals total.

Hence the maximum length of any string in L(G) is 3, but the given string has length 17. Therefore it cannot be generated.

No

The grammar can only generate strings of length at most 4 (S→NT13 NT22 gives 2 terminals; S→NT6 NT30 gives between 2 and 4 terminals), so it cannot produce a 17‐terminal string.  
No

After examining the rules, the only ways to expand S are

1. S→NT13 NT22 → 2 terminals (length 2)  
2. S→NT6 NT30:
   • if NT30→ terminal, total length 2  
   • if NT30→NT23 NT32 and NT23→NT21 NT11, then NT6, NT21, NT11, NT32 each go to one terminal → length 4

No derivation can yield a string of length 18. Therefore the given string cannot be generated.  

No

To generate a 20‐symbol string, S→NT6 NT30 would need NT6 to yield one symbol and NT30 to yield 19 symbols—but NT30 can produce at most 3 terminals (via NT23→NT21 NT11 and NT32), and NT6 only one. And the only other option S→NT13 NT22 yields exactly 2 symbols. Hence the given 20‐symbol string cannot be derived.

To see why the given string of length 21 cannot be generated, observe that from the start symbol S there are only two productions:

  S → NT13 NT22  
  S → NT6 NT30

Each of NT13, NT22, NT6, NT30 ultimately produces either a single terminal or at most two terminals (in the case NT30→NT23 NT32 and NT23→NT21 NT11).  Tracing the longest possible expansion:

  S→NT6 NT30  
  NT30→NT23 NT32  
  NT23→NT21 NT11

yields exactly four nonterminals [NT6, NT21, NT11, NT32], each of which maps to a single terminal.  Hence the maximal string‐length S can generate is 4.  Our input has length 21, so it cannot be in the language.

The grammar’s only binary expansions are  
 S→NT6 NT30 and NT30→NT23 NT32 and NT23→NT21 NT11.  
All other rules go directly to a single terminal.  
Thus any S→… derivation yields at most 4 terminals (either 2 via S→NT13 NT22 or 4 via S→NT6 NT23 NT32).  
A 22‐token string cannot be generated.  
No

The grammar’s only start‐rules are  
  S → NT13 NT22  (each of NT13, NT22 is a single terminal → length 2)  
  S → NT6 NT30  

NT6 and NT30 expand only as follows:  
  NT6 → terminal  (length 1)  
  NT30 → NT23 NT32 (NT23 → either two terminals or one terminal; NT32 → one terminal)  
       → terminal  

So S can generate at most 1 (from NT6) + 1–3 (from NT30) = 2–4 terminals. The input string has length 22, far too long.  

No

We observe that NT6, NT13, NT22, NT21, NT11, NT32, NT23 and NT30 all either produce a single terminal or else exactly two nonterminals (in CNF).  In particular:

• NT6, NT13, NT22, NT21, NT11, NT32, NT30→terminal only, so each covers exactly one symbol when used as a leaf.  
• The only binary productions are  
  S→NT6 NT30  
  S→NT13 NT22  
  NT30→NT23 NT32  
  NT23→NT21 NT11  
and each of NT21, NT11, NT32 is again terminal‐only.

Hence any parse tree is a full binary tree where each internal node has exactly two children, and each leaf produces exactly one input symbol.  A full binary tree with k internal nodes has k+1 leaves.  The largest chain of binary expansions starting from S is

 S→NT6 NT30→NT23 NT32→NT21 NT11

which has 3 binary nodes (S, NT30, NT23) and thus 4 leaves, i.e. can generate at most 4 terminals.  Our input has 24 tokens, far beyond what this grammar can yield.  Therefore it cannot be generated.  

No

The grammar is in strict Chomsky normal form, and the only way to derive more than 1 terminal from S is via

  S → NT6 NT30  
     NT30 → NT23 NT32  
     NT23 → NT21 NT11

Counting leaves:

• If NT30 → (one terminal), S→two leaves ⇒ length 2  
• If NT30 → NT23 NT32 but NT23→terminal, NT32→terminal, S⇒3 leaves ⇒ length 3  
• If full expansion NT23→NT21 NT11, each of these and NT32 are preterminals ⇒ 4 leaves ⇒ length 4  

No further binary expansions exist, so no string longer than 4 terminals can be generated. The given string has 25 tokens, so it cannot be in the language.

To generate a string of length > 4, S would have to expand NT30 recursively, but NT30 has no recursive rules—its maximum yield is 3 terminals—so S can only produce lengths 2, 3, or 4. The given string has length 25, so it cannot be generated.

After inspecting the productions, the longest string S can generate has length 4 (via S→NT6 NT30→t… (1) + NT23 NT32→(up to 3) = 4). Since the given string has length 25, it cannot be generated.

  NT21, NT11, NT32 → each exactly one terminal.

Hence any derivation from S produces either 2 terminals (1+1) or 4 terminals (1+3). The given string has 26 terminals, so it cannot be derived.
